    "markdown": "---\nformat:\n  html:\n    css: styles.css\n    embed-resources: TRUE\n    code-fold: true\n    page-layout: full\n    fig_caption: yes\n---\n\n\n\n::: {.cell}\n\n:::\n\n::: {.cell}\n\n:::\n\n\n::: narrow-section\n\n::: {.cell}\n::: {.cell-output-display}\n```{=html}\n<div id=\"grid-container\" style=\"display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr); justify-items: center;\">\n<div id=\"highlight-text\">565</div>\n<div id=\"highlight-text\">684</div>\n<div style=\"display: block; &#10;              color: #ff6400; &#10;              font-size: 1.25em; &#10;              font-family: Graphik; &#10;              font-weight: bold; &#10;              text-align: center;\">High<br>Indeterminacy</div>\n<div id=\"bold-text\">Currently Eligible for<br>Parole but in Prison</div>\n<div id=\"bold-text\">Eligible for Parole in<br>the next 1-5 years</div>\n<div id=\"bold-text\">\n<span class=\"tippy html-widget html-fill-item-overflow-hidden html-fill-item\" height=\"338px\" id=\"htmlwidget-343c8b36ee09d70ab272\" width=\"100%\"></span>\n<script type=\"application/json\" data-for=\"htmlwidget-343c8b36ee09d70ab272\">{\"x\":{\"opts\":{\"placement\":\"bottom\",\"flip\":true,\"theme\":\"light\",\"content\":\"To compare the degrees of indeterminacy, or unpredictability\\n   of time served, of prison-sentencing systems of different jurisdictions,\\n   we use a qualitative ranking framework based on the Robina Institute's\\n   Prison-release Discretion And Prison Population Size Report.<br><br><b>High Indeterminacy<\\/b>: >60-80 percent indeterminacy (first prospect of release at 20-39.99 percent of judicial maximum).\"},\"text\":\"<span aria-label=\\\"To compare the degrees of indeterminacy, or unpredictability\\n   of time served, of prison-sentencing systems of different jurisdictions,\\n   we use a qualitative ranking framework based on the Robina Institute's\\n   Prison-release Discretion And Prison Population Size Report.<br><br><b>High Indeterminacy<\\/b>: >60-80 percent indeterminacy (first prospect of release at 20-39.99 percent of judicial maximum).\\\" tabindex=\\\"0\\\" role=\\\"button\\\">Prison Sentencing<br>System&#9432;<\\/span>\"},\"evals\":[],\"jsHooks\":[]}</script>\n</div>\n</div>\n```\n:::\n:::\n\n:::\n\n<br>\n\n\n\n::: panel-tabset \n\n## Parole Eligibility\n\n<center>\n\n::: {.cell}\n::: {.cell-output-display}\n```{=html}\n<div id=\"body-section\">\n<br/>\n<div id=\"big-section-title\">How is Parole Release Eligibility Determined?</div>\n<br/>\n<div id=\"regular-text\">In New Hampshire, sentences have a minimum and a maximum term. However, if a sentence has a maximum of over one year (i.e. a felony sentence), the judge must also impose a 'disciplinary period' of incarceration of 150 days per year of the minimum term that can then be reduced through credit for good conduct. For example, a three to eight year sentence would have a 450 day 'disciplinary period' added on to the minimum term. If a sentence of imprisonment is imposed, the maximum term may not exceed: life for second-degree murder, 15 years for a class A felony, seven years for a class B felony, or one year for a class A misdemeanor. Some crimes carry mandatory minimum sentences. For example, a second or subsequent conviction for the felonious use of a firearm carries a mandatory minimum sentence of three years. A conviction under the state's version of the Armed Career Criminal Act carries a minimum sentence of ten years. Prisoners may be released on parole at the expiration of the minimum terms of their sentences, plus the disciplinary period of incarceration that must be imposed during sentencing, and minus any credit for good conduct. So, for example, if an individual is given a sentence of 10 to 25 years, they must serve their 10 year minimum and, in addition, 1,500 days (or about four years, one month, and 10 days) of a disciplinary period. However, through good time credit, the inmate can pare the 14 years plus that must be served before parole release eligibility back down to 10 years. Thus, the disciplinary period and good time are designed to offset each other.</div>\n<br/>\n<br/>\n<div id=\"big-section-title\">People who are Eligible for Parole</div>\n<br/>\n<div id=\"bar-chart\">\n<div id=\"htmlwidget-cf54f01572c467b5f0b2\" style=\"width:100%;height:454px;\" class=\"highchart html-widget \"></div>\n<script type=\"application/json\" data-for=\"htmlwidget-cf54f01572c467b5f0b2\">{\"x\":{\"hc_opts\":{\"chart\":{\"reflow\":true,\"width\":500,\"height\":350},\"title\":{\"text\":\"People who are Parole Eligible but Still in Prison by Race in 2020\"},\"yAxis\":{\"title\":{\"text\":null},\"labels\":{\"enabled\":false}},\"credits\":{\"enabled\":false},\"exporting\":{\"enabled\":true},\"boost\":{\"enabled\":false},\"plotOptions\":{\"series\":{\"label\":{\"enabled\":false},\"turboThreshold\":0,\"animation\":false,\"cursor\":\"pointer\",\"borderWidth\":3,\"minPointLength\":4},\"treemap\":{\"layoutAlgorithm\":\"squarified\"},\"accessibility\":{\"enabled\":true,\"keyboardNavigation\":{\"enabled\":true},\"linkedDescription\":\"TBD\",\"landmarkVerbosity\":\"one\"},\"area\":{\"accessibility\":{\"description\":\"TBD\"}}},\"series\":[{\"group\":\"group\",\"data\":[{\"state\":\"New Hampshire\",\"race\":\"White, non-Hispanic\",\"n\":481,\"prop\":0.868231046931408,\"yearendpop_ped\":554,\"prop_label\":\"87%\",\"tooltip\":\"<b>New Hampshire - White, non-Hispanic<\\/b><br>87%<br>\",\"y\":86.82310469314079,\"color\":\"#FDE725\",\"name\":\"White, non-Hispanic\",\"colorv\":\"White, non-Hispanic\"},{\"state\":\"New Hampshire\",\"race\":\"Hispanic, any race\",\"n\":36,\"prop\":0.06498194945848375,\"yearendpop_ped\":554,\"prop_label\":\"6%\",\"tooltip\":\"<b>New Hampshire - Hispanic, any race<\\/b><br>6%<br>\",\"y\":6.498194945848375,\"color\":\"#2C6079\",\"name\":\"Hispanic, any race\",\"colorv\":\"Hispanic, any race\"},{\"state\":\"New Hampshire\",\"race\":\"Black, non-Hispanic\",\"n\":34,\"prop\":0.06137184115523465,\"